# Git & Documentation Rules

## Commit Messages — Conventional Commits

Every commit must follow the Conventional Commits format. No exceptions.

```
<type>(<scope>): <short description>

[optional body — explain WHY, not WHAT]
```

### Types

| Type | When to use |
|---|---|
| `feat` | A new feature visible to the user or API consumer |
| `fix` | A bug fix |
| `refactor` | Code change that neither fixes a bug nor adds a feature |
| `chore` | Tooling, deps, config — no production code change |
| `docs` | README, ADR, comments only |
| `test` | Adding or fixing tests |
| `perf` | Performance improvement |

### Scope — use the module name

`auth`, `user`, `server`, `channel`, `message`, `realtime`, `shared`, `db`, `redis`

### Examples

```
# ✅ correct
feat(message): add soft delete with ownership check
fix(invite): prevent use after revocation
refactor(user): extract cache logic into UserCacheRepository
chore(deps): upgrade drizzle-orm to 0.31.0
docs(adr): record decision to use snapshot pattern for message sender
perf(message): add compound index on channelId + createdAt

# ❌ wrong
fix bug
update message service
WIP
temp
```

### When AI suggests a commit

Always propose the full commit message in the format above.
If the change spans multiple concerns, propose splitting it into separate commits.
Never suggest a single commit for changes across more than two modules.

