## Architecture Decision Records (ADR)

An ADR must be written whenever a decision meets any of these criteria:

- A specific technology was chosen over alternatives (e.g. Mongoose over native driver)
- A design pattern was introduced (e.g. snapshot pattern, Facade, Observer)
- A tradeoff was consciously accepted (e.g. stale avatar in exchange for fewer round trips)
- A previously considered approach was rejected and should not be revisited

### Location

```
docs/
  adr/
    001-hybrid-database.md
    002-snapshot-pattern-for-message-sender.md
    003-redis-sliding-ttl-for-user-cache.md
    004-stateless-auth-without-blacklist.md
```

### ADR format — keep it short

```markdown
# ADR-{number}: {title}

**Status:** Accepted

## Context
What problem were we solving? What constraints existed?

## Decision
What did we decide to do?

## Consequences
What becomes easier? What becomes harder? What do we accept as a tradeoff?
```

### Examples of decisions that already need an ADR in this project

| ADR | Decision |
|---|---|
| `001-hybrid-database` | Postgres for relational data, MongoDB for messages |
| `002-snapshot-pattern` | Embed sender info in message document instead of hydrating from Postgres |
| `003-redis-user-cache` | Cache user profiles with sliding TTL + invalidate on update |
| `004-stateless-auth` | No JWT blacklist in MVP — accept 15-minute window on logout |

### When AI must prompt for an ADR

If a task involves any of the following, AI must remind the developer to write or update an ADR before closing the task:

- Changing which database stores a type of data
- Adding or removing a design pattern from the codebase
- Choosing between two libraries or approaches
- Accepting a known limitation or tradeoff

Example reminder:
> "This changes how user identity is resolved in messages. Consider writing ADR-002 to record why snapshot pattern was chosen over runtime hydration."

